Based on the search results, I found detailed information about tapable SyncHook with the Car accelerate example:

## Tapable SyncHook Example with Car Accelerate

The best practice is to expose all hooks of a class in a hooks property. Here's a Car example with an accelerate hook using SyncHook:

```javascript
class Car {
  constructor() {
    this.hooks = {
      accelerate: new SyncHook(["newSpeed"]),
      brake: new SyncHook(),
      calculateRoutes: new AsyncParallelHook(["source", "target", "routesList"])
    };
  }
}
```


### Using tap() to Add Plugins

You can use the tap method to add a consumer and receive arguments:

```javascript
myCar.hooks.accelerate.tap("LoggerPlugin", (newSpeed) => 
  console.log(`Accelerating to ${newSpeed}`)
);
```

For sync hooks, tap is the only valid method to add a plugin.

### Calling the Hook

The class declaring these hooks needs to call them using the call method:

```javascript
setSpeed(newSpeed) {
  // following call returns undefined even when you returned values
  this.hooks.accelerate.call(newSpeed);
}
```


### Key Characteristics of SyncHook

Each hook can be tapped with one or several functions. How they are executed depends on the hook type. A basic hook (without "Waterfall", "Bail" or "Loop" in its name) simply calls every function it tapped in a row.


