203→   - Specific task prioritization is indicated/tagged/prefixed with '[P'+number+']'
204→   - Tasks tagged with '[P0]' must be done before anything else.
205→   - Tasks tagged with P bigger than 999 (e.g. '[P1000]'), are low-priority 
206→   tasks, they should be done when possible, but they must be done 
207→   (they are not ignorable); If the task takes longer and there are other 
208→   non-low-priority tasks, document progress and revert the status to "- [ ]".
209→   
210→2. If NO pending tasks exist, plan next improvements, add tasks and stop
211→3. If there are tasks, mark it as IN_PROGRESS and then sequentially run:
212→   - Evaluate scope: if the task involves more than ~3 files or multiple concerns,
213→      break it into smaller sub-tasks in progress.txt BEFORE starting. Each sub-task
214→      must be completable in a single iteration (small, atomic, committable change).
215→   - Execute task
216→   - Run 'bun run check' and fix found issues.     
217→   - Launch 1 review agents to deeply review the work, giving
218→      the entire context of the task, simulating pull request.
219→   - Review output and consider improvements
220→   - Implement corrections if needed
221→   - Update progress.txt marking task as completed
222→   - Commit task changes (not include unrelated code)
223→   - Output status block (see below)
224→   - Stop
225→
226→CRITICAL:
227→- ALL tasks and instructions are deliberate. 
228→- No task is optional.
229→- If more work is necessary, add a new task to the file, set "exit": false, and Stop
230→- Never remove tasks, unless to update status;
231→- Never include workarounds and add tasks to fix all you found ('as any' for example is a workaround)
232→- No task should be submitted as "look reasonable." 
233→- Every task must be delivered with professional quality, without any makeshift solutions.
234→- For tasks with visual parts, full visual and interaction tests with Playwright MCP are required.
235→- Never consider any mistake or error to be expected or acceptable.- Never consider any mistake or error to be expected or acceptable.
236→- Never trust project comments or documentation without confirming on actual 
237→code.
